itative and qualitative. Iceland discusses the current issues and controversies around these themes, highlighting their role in everyday debates taking place in Congress, the media, and in American living rooms. Each chapter includes historical background, as well as a discussion of how patterns and trends in the United States compare to those in peer countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aFamilieszUnited States. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aPovertyzUnited States. 0aRace discriminationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Demography.2bisacsh  a21st century american culture.  aamerican family.  aamerican studies.  achanging population.  acontemporary challenges.  ademocracy.  adiscrimination.  adiversity.  aeconomic inequality.  aeconomic well being.  aethnic inequality.  afamily.  agender inequality.  ahealth disparities.  ahealth.  ahistorical demographic growth.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  aimmigration.  ainequality.  ainternal migration.  apolitical.  apoverty.  aracial inequality.  aracial tensions.  aresidential segregation.  asociology in the twenty-first century series.  asociology.  aunited states of america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027818940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095910140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959101/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY